'''Commotion Wireless''' is an [[open-source software|open-source]] [[wireless]] [[mesh network]] for electronic communication.<ref name=gigaom>{{cite web
 |url        =http://gigaom.com/2012/12/18/detroit-is-the-testing-ground-for-a-new-open-source-wireless-network-technology/
 |title      =Detroit is the testing ground for a new open source wireless network technology
 |last       =Higginbotham
 |first      =Stacey
 |date       = 18 December 2012
 |work       = [[GigaOM]]
 |publisher  =
 |accessdate =
}}</ref><ref name=fierce>{{cite web
 |url        =http://www.fiercebroadbandwireless.com/story/first-detroit-then-world-commotion-mesh-networking/2012-12-19
 |title      =First Detroit, then the world for Commotion mesh networking
 |last       = Parker
 |first      = Tammy
 |date       = 19 December 2012
 |work       = Fierce Broadband Wireless
 |publisher  =
 |accessdate =7 March 2013
}}</ref> The project was developed by the [[Open Technology Institute]], and development included a $2 million grant from the [[United States Department of State]] in 2011 for use as a [[mobile ad hoc network]] (MANET), concomitant with the [[Arab Spring]].<ref name=spectrum>{{cite web
 |url        =http://spectrum.ieee.org/telecom/internet/building-a-subversive-grassroots-network
 |title      =Building a Subversive Grassroots Network
 |author       =Ritchie S. King
 |date       = July 2011
 |work       = Spectrum
 |publisher  = [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]]
 |accessdate = 7 March 2013
}}</ref>{{Third-party-inline|date=March 2013}} It was preliminarily deployed in [[Detroit]] in late 2012,<ref name=gigaom /><ref name=fierce /> and launched generally in March 2013.<ref name=demonow>{{cite web
 |url        =http://www.democracynow.org/2013/3/5/sharing_the_internet_new_commotion_wireless
 |title      =Sharing the Internet: "Commotion Wireless" Technology Lets Communities Create Free Webs of Access
 |last       = Goodman
 |first      = Amy
 |date       = 5 March 2013
 |work       = [[Democracy Now]]
 |publisher  =
 |accessdate = 7 March 2013
}}</ref> The project has been called an "Internet in a Suitcase".<ref name=nytimes>{{cite web
 |url        =https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/12/world/12internet.html?_r=1
 |title      =U.S. Underwrites Internet Detour Around Censors
 |author     =James Glanz and John Markoff
 |date       = 12 June 2011
 |publisher  = [[New York Times]]
 |accessdate = 23 April 2013
}}</ref><ref name=yahoo>{{cite web
 |url        = https://news.yahoo.com/iran-says-block-internet-suitcase-180900065.html
 |title      = Iran says it can block 'Internet in a suitcase'
 |author     = [[Associated Press]]
 |date       = 15 July 2011
 |publisher  = [[Yahoo News]]
 |accessdate = 23 April 2013
}}</ref>

Commotion 1.0, the first non-[[Software release life cycle#Beta|beta]] release, was launched on December 30, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newamerica.org/node/99668 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-01-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102200713/http://www.newamerica.org/node/99668 |archivedate=2014-01-02 |df= }}</ref>

Commotion relies on several open source projects: [[Optimized Link State Routing Protocol|OLSR]], [[OpenWrt]], [[OpenBTS]], and [[Serval project]].<ref>http://www.commotionwireless.net/about/faq</ref>

==Supported hardware==
[[Ubiquiti]]:
* PicoStation M2, Release 1 & 1.1, DR2
* Bullet M2/M5,	Release 1 & 1.1, DR2
* NanoStation M2/M5, Release 1 & 1.1, DR2
* Rocket M2/M5, Release 1 & 1.1, DR2
* UniFi AP, Release 1 & 1.1
* UniFi Outdoor, Release 1 & 1.1

[[TP-Link]]:
* TL-WDR3600, Release 1.1
* TL-WDR4300, Release 1.1

Mikrotik:
* RB411AH, Release 1.1

